{
  "summary": "This paper proposes 'knowledge unlearning' as a post-hoc, efficient method to remove specific token sequences from Pretrained Language Models (LMs) to address privacy concerns like the 'Right To Be Forgotten' (RTBF). It applies the unlikelihood training objective to maximize the loss for target sequences, effectively making the LM 'forget' them. The method demonstrates a reduction in memorization metrics (Extraction Likelihood and Memorization Accuracy) with little to no degradation in general LM performance, and is claimed to be computationally efficient.",
  "strengths": [
    {
      "point": "Addresses a highly relevant and timely problem regarding privacy risks in large language models, particularly in the context of the 'Right To Be Forgotten' (RTBF).",
      "evidence": "Pretrained Language Models (LMs) can memorize sensitive personal information from their training data, posing privacy risks. There is a need for a post-hoc, efficient method to remove specific knowledge from LMs to address privacy concerns, such as the 'Right To Be Forgotten' (RTBF)."
    },
    {
      "point": "Proposes a conceptually sound approach by leveraging the unlikelihood training objective for targeted knowledge removal.",
      "evidence": "The paper proposes 'knowledge unlearning' as a post-hoc method... This is achieved by applying the unlikelihood training objective, which essentially maximizes the loss for target sequences, effectively making the LM 'forget' them."
    },
    {
      "point": "Offers a post-hoc and computationally efficient alternative to costly retraining or data preprocessing methods.",
      "evidence": "Knowledge unlearning is orders of magnitude more computationally efficient than data preprocessing methods. It is estimated to be 3,500,000x more efficient in terms of FLOPs compared to pretraining OPT."
    },
    {
      "point": "Provides valuable empirical exploration into factors affecting unlearning, such as sequential vs. batch unlearning and domain dependency.",
      "evidence": "Investigated the impact of forgetting s samples at once (batch) versus forgetting them in smaller chunks sequentially... Analyzed how different data domains (e.g., code, emails, unstructured text) affect the difficulty of unlearning and LM performance degradation."
    },
    {
      "point": "Demonstrates effectiveness in reducing memorization, as quantified by Extraction Likelihood (EL) and Memorization Accuracy (MA).",
      "evidence": "Knowledge unlearning effectively reduces Extraction Likelihood (EL) and Memorization Accuracy (MA) below a defined 'Forgetting Threshold' for target token sequences. For GPT-Neo 1.3B, EL$_{10}$ drops from 62.2 to 30.4 and MA drops from 36.7 to 36.4 when unlearning to match OPT."
    }
  ],
  "weaknesses": [
    {
      "point": "The core technical mechanism (unlikelihood training) is not novel, and its application for targeted suppression lacks sufficient differentiation from prior work on controlled generation and model editing.",
      "evidence": "The core technical mechanism, 'unlikelihood training objective,' is not novel in itself... The summary does not provide any evidence of a novel formulation or modification of this objective beyond its direct application to memorized data."
    },
    {
      "point": "The 'Extraction Likelihood (EL)' metric, introduced as novel, lacks rigorous comparative analysis and justification against existing memorization/extraction metrics.",
      "evidence": "The paper introduces 'Extraction Likelihood (EL)' as a novel metric... The critic should have pushed harder on the novelty and effectiveness of *this specific contribution*."
    },
    {
      "point": "The empirical definition of 'forgotten' is ambiguous, underspecified, lacks robustness guarantees, and its alignment with formal privacy notions or RTBF is not adequately established.",
      "evidence": "A token sequence is considered 'forgotten' when its EL and MA values fall below the average EL and MA calculated on token sequences not seen during training (validation corpora). This definition is highly sensitive to the choice, quality, and representativeness of this 'validation corpora.'"
    },
    {
      "point": "Reports of performance improvements on some benchmarks post-unlearning are highly counter-intuitive and lack a detailed mechanistic explanation.",
      "evidence": "For some benchmarks like Lambada, it even shows substantial improvements... Such large improvements warrant a dedicated analysis in the full paper to explain this phenomenon."
    },
    {
      "point": "The claim of 'little to no degradation' in general LM performance lacks comprehensive quantitative and statistical support across all evaluated benchmarks.",
      "evidence": "The paper mentions 9 benchmarks, but the critique only focuses on Lambada."
    },
    {
      "point": "The distinction and procedural differences between 'unlearning to match OPT' and 'unlearning until the threshold is met' are unclear, hindering reproducibility and interpretation of results.",
      "evidence": "The distinction between 'unlearning to match OPT' and 'unlearning until the threshold is met' for privacy results is not clearly explained in terms of the unlearning process or stopping criteria."
    },
    {
      "point": "The selection of '15,000 easy to extract examples' for target data is vague, impacting reproducibility and limiting generalizability to harder-to-extract sensitive data.",
      "evidence": "The selection process for the '15,000 examples from 16 domains of the Pile corpora, known to be somewhat easy to extract' as target data for unlearning is not detailed. The phrase 'known to be somewhat easy to extract' is vague and does not provide an objective criterion for replication."
    },
    {
      "point": "The paper lacks a rigorous quantitative comparison of its efficiency and privacy efficacy against data deduplication, a key alternative for mitigating memorization.",
      "evidence": "The summary mentions OPT models serving as a comparison to 'data deduplication.' The critic does not engage with this comparison at all. This is a missed opportunity."
    },
    {
      "point": "The ethical implications of the 'Right To Be Forgotten' are not adequately discussed beyond technical verbatim extraction metrics, failing to address broader socio-ethical and legal perspectives.",
      "evidence": "The paper's motivation is RTBF... how well do they truly align with the legal and ethical implications of RTBF? Are there scenarios where EL/MA are low, but a user would still consider their data 'unforgotten'?"
    }
  ],
  "questions": [
    {
      "question": "Please provide a dedicated section thoroughly comparing 'knowledge unlearning' to at least three specific prior works using unlikelihood or similar objectives for *targeted content removal/suppression* (e.g., in controlled generation or model editing). Detail differences in objectives, training procedures, and intended outcomes (e.g., privacy vs. style/fact correction). Additionally, formally define the Extraction Likelihood (EL) metric and present a rigorous comparative study against at least two established memorization/extraction metrics, quantifying correlation, computational cost, and sensitivity to parameters, while explicitly justifying EL's unique advantages for privacy leakage detection.",
      "motivation": "The core technical mechanism (unlikelihood) is not novel, and its application needs precise contextualization. The claimed novelty of EL as a metric for privacy is central to the paper but lacks rigorous validation and comparison, which is essential for scientific credibility and understanding its utility."
    },
    {
      "question": "Please provide a comprehensive description of the 'validation corpora' used to define the 'forgotten' threshold, including its source, size, domain, and a detailed methodology for how its 'unseen' status was rigorously confirmed. Explicitly state the statistical measure for 'average' EL/MA and perform a sensitivity analysis showing how the 'forgetting threshold' changes with variations in the validation corpus or outlier handling. Finally, provide a principled discussion on how this empirical threshold relates to common understandings and desiderata of privacy, rather than just technical metrics.",
      "motivation": "The definition of 'forgotten' is foundational to the paper's privacy claims but is currently underspecified and lacks robustness guarantees. Its connection to real-world privacy expectations needs thorough justification."
    },
    {
      "question": "The reported performance improvements on certain benchmarks post-unlearning are highly counter-intuitive. Please provide a detailed mechanistic explanation for this phenomenon. Hypotheses such as regularization effects, removal of noisy data, or benchmark-specific artifacts need to be substantiated. Additionally, present a comprehensive table detailing mean performance and statistical significance (e.g., p-values) across *all nine benchmarks* for the original model and both unlearning targets, along with plots showing privacy-performance trade-off curves throughout the unlearning process.",
      "motivation": "Unexplained performance improvements raise significant questions about the experimental setup, the understanding of the unlearning process, or potential artifacts. A rigorous analysis is crucial for the credibility of the evaluation and understanding the privacy-utility trade-off."
    },
    {
      "question": "Please provide explicit algorithmic pseudocode or detailed step-by-step instructions for *each* unlearning configuration ('unlearning to match OPT' and 'unlearning until threshold is met'), including precise termination conditions and hyperparameters. Justify *why* 'matching OPT' is a relevant privacy goal, considering its EL$_{10}$ compared to the 'forgotten' threshold. Furthermore, conduct a rigorous quantitative comparison of the proposed method's efficiency (FLOPs/compute) and privacy efficacy (EL/MA reduction) against a standard data deduplication pipeline applied *during pre-training* to achieve a comparable reduction in memorization.",
      "motivation": "Ambiguity in experimental setup hinders reproducibility. A clear rationale for unlearning targets is needed. A quantitative comparison against a key alternative like data deduplication is essential to substantiate claims of efficiency and demonstrate the method's value proposition."
    },
    {
      "question": "Provide a clear, reproducible methodology for identifying the '15,000 easy to extract examples,' potentially including scripts or explicit criteria, and discuss the limitations of evaluating solely on 'easy' data and how the method might perform on harder-to-extract information. Finally, include at least 2-3 detailed, side-by-side illustrative examples demonstrating successful extraction from the *original* model and the *failure* of these same extraction attempts on the *unlearned* model, linking observed behavior to EL/MA scores.",
      "motivation": "Reproducibility is fundamental. Evaluating only on 'easy' data limits generalizability. Concrete examples are crucial to visibly demonstrate the method's practical impact and efficacy in preventing privacy breaches."
    }
  ],
  "scores": {
    "correctness": 3,
    "novelty": 2,
    "recommendation": "borderline",
    "confidence": 5
  }
}
